<Text>I took my friend here on a whim, never eaten here before but it was close to his hotel.  I highly recommend the house tea which is served sweetened.  I order the chicken special which was awesome.  My daughter wanted the soup but I wasn't sure if she would like it, the owner offered her a sample cup on the house.  It was almost a full order.  She asked for seconds and he brought her an even larger bowl and didn't even charge for the first.  After we finished our dinner, the owner gave us a free desert to try.  Also very yummy and rich.  It rare to have this type of mom and pop service in the City any more and for them to offer samplings just to see the enjoyment of their cuisine.< /Text></record>

<review>We stopped by here while visiting SF. This is not a review for the food as we didn't get a chance to try it. Rather this is a review for the lack of respect for the customer. We parked near by and walked to this restaurant. I tried to open the door but it was locked. While checking the other side of the corner to see if there is another door two men unlocked the door talking in their native language one trying to convince the other to allow us to enter. The other one didn't want us to enter for some reason. There was still 2 hours to their closing time. I am guessing it was because the restaurant was full and/or we had 2 small children. I don't know. While they are talking to each other I asked whether they are open. They kept ignoring me and continue their discussion. Soon the guy was convinced and signaled us to enter at which point I was pretty annoyed by the whole ordeal. I thanked them and we walked away. David Joekel</name>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
Everything we tried was amazing.  Go during late afternoon when it's not crowded as the food can take a little bit but is worth the wait.  I had the lamb kebab couscous and it was simply awesome.  My girlfriend had a chicken shwarma, and the grilled wrap that it comes in makes its perfect.  We also ordered some bread, pita, and hummus, which were all about average....but they also have a roasted red pepper spread/dip that you HAVE to try.  The staff seemed pretty quiet and reserved, and we just started talking to the cook and telling him how much we enjoyed it all.  He seemed appreciative and offered us mint tea and a pistachio dessert. Nice little place, very reasonably priced......and I was completely stuffed when I left.  Even if you know nothing about moroccan cuisine - you'll be just fine.  Just get the lamb or chicken kebabs with couscous and you'll be happy.<//review>

<Text>Stopped by here for Sunday afternoon brunch and the food was delicious. I usually opt for Aicha's Moroccan which is only two blocks away, but I am definitely glad I decided to try something new instead. We ordered the breakfast burrito with merguez added as well as the shakshouka, both of which were delicious. I also ordered the mint tea, which was absolute heaven - fresh, minty, and just the right amount of sweet. Each table also receives an Acme baguette that is served with a delicious harrissa paste.

As someone who eats halal meat only, wherever I travel I usually find myself at Mediterranean type places when I crave meat, and so I've come to develop a rather high standard when it comes to this particular cuisine. I can honestly say that this place has hands down the best merguez I have ever tasted - the lamb was fresh, juicy, and perfectly spiced. I would return here just for the merguez. In fact, I look forward to returning for lunch and dinner and sampling what else they have to offer.

Overall, if you're in the area and are looking for an affordable and delicious meal, you won't go wrong with Cafe Zitouna!</Text>< name>
Ming De<//name>
</record>

<Review>Current Hours are:

Tues-Thurs: 11:30am to 9:00pm Fri: 2:00pm to 9:00pm
Sat and Sun: 11:30am to 9:00pm Closed Monday

We stopped into this light and airy corner restaurant for lunch and were amazed at the wonderful flavors of the various "fait maison" dishes served.  We ordered a delicious spread of appetizers, including the Breek (Tunisian cr√™pe), the Moroccan eggplant and pita, and the perfectly spiced Merguez sausage.  The fresh mint tea (lightly sweetened) was a very refreshing accompaniment to the meal.  Finishing off the lunch was a homemade pudding featuring essence of geranium and topped with ground pistachios.  Excellent end to a perfect lunch.

Within a day, we were back at Caf√© Zitouna this time for dinner.  We ordered the Mosaic of kebabs (lamb, chicken and Merguez) and the lamb stew couscous, both served with a basket of fresh French bread.  Once again, chef was spot on with the dishes.

Unlike many of the city's other restaurants, all of the dishes at Caf√© Zitouna are made in house (including the owner's excellent Harissa sauce).  Both times the welcome we received was warm and genuine.

Thank you for two excellent meals, Chef!  We look forward to our next visit to Caf√© Zitouna.  A bient√¥t!</Review><Pics>None< /Pics><resp>None< /resp><gmap_id>0x80858094439acddf:0x698cf43d4c42b19c< /gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<review>Beautiful mosaic steps in Sunset area of San Frsncisco. Both sides of the steps have very beautiful a d delightful garden. You can see the view of San Francisco bay and Marina district clearly on the clear day. Upon coming on top of the steps, you can climb up a zigzag stairs up to the top of the hill where the Grand View Park is located. From the Grand View Park you can see everywhere of San Francisco, down town sky line, the Golden Gate park with De Young Museum poking through, the Twin Peaks near by, the Land End etc. It is a very good experience. Best of all, it is usually not very crowded and there are plenty of roadside parking nearby with need to pay for parking.<//review><pictures>[{'url': < text>
It is a fabulous spot for pictures with the mosaic steps on the stairway.  Walking up and down the steps would be a good exercise for the day.  View from the top let you see the Pacific Ocean.  You will enjoy the great view during sunset.  So get your camera ready.

By the way, bring a jacket since it could be chilly and windy...<//text>

<Text>I've been here twice. The stairs are pretty. There aren't very many of them, but interesting to see and I wish more stairs were like this elsewhere in cities. There is a spectacular view from the top, almost 360 degrees and see a lot of the city at once. Great for a sunset too. There's another small stair with mosaic nearby too. There's also a bus stop at the bottom, so you can go even if you don't have a car.</Text>< user_name>

<pics>None< /pics><name>Paul Lynch</name>< text>
Don't even think about eating here! New owners have completely ruined this place. They have erected massive glass screens over the counter area and speak to you through an EXTREMELY LOUD PA system. It is deafening. I have never seen anything like this. The loudness combined with the broken English is almost impossible to understand. Mean, scary, aggressive lady behind the glass. There were three customers in the shop and we waited almost 30 minutes for our orders. We only received our orders after we banded together and demanded our food. The food, if you can call it that, was uneatable. The fish was oily (low temperature cooking) and tainted with a rancid oil taste. The batter, fell off of the fish. I had ordered 3 pieces and threw away 2. The coleslaw tasted of raw fish juice. Disgusting. Threw it away. Stay away, far away from this place. I never write Yelp reviews - consider this review a public service. Minus 4 stars is my rating. Pray that I live through the night.</text>

The fish is the bomb!!!
I was there 3weeks ago.
The place is a bit freaky looking inside and out.  I walked in to find all the tables and chairs had tape on them.  Looked like a crime scene but it was obvious no dining was allowed indoors due to COVID.
The lady at the counter addressed me through a cheap loud microphone.  I hadn't been to an H.Salt in over 25 years, the menu was a bit overwhelming but she was patient.
The fish and coleslaw were fresh and delicious OMG!
The fish was a tad too oily but a few napkins solved that. SOOO GOOD!
If you can, definitely call ahead to place your order.  I was the only customer and waited about 30 minutes.< /Text>

You know first off the restaurant is no longer H.Salt Fish & Chips. When I arrived I noticed that the sign on the building they had removed the H Salt and the only thing left was fish and chips. Park, walk, eat, and shop.</text>

<Name>David Juarez<//Name>< text>
You will remember this review, so read on. When you walk into this place hungry- you are excited. The young blue eyed brown haired girl at the counter is super sweet. She really works hard to be on point in that American Pie kind of customer service and feel.We had ordered a Combo which she cheerily suggested  and also the standard Fish and Chips. After she was bombarded by a slew of creepy and sad customers and 1 bum that walked in- she still managed to treat everyone with respect and politeness. This chick is new I thought, she is how we all were at 17- young and bright full of eagerness to be a good employee. 25 minutes later, our food was ready. Excited, I go to the counter. Now she had asked if I needed anything else- and thats when the troll owner chimed in-" that will be 75 cents more". I felt bad for the young girl. This owner clearly needs that 75 cents enough to embarrass and undermine her only hard working employee.

The food: When I first saw the pile of grease that sat before us I said. "You've got to be kidding- is she trying to give us a heart attack" Here's why: for the 37 dollars we paid- this was all kinds of wrong. This owner needs to stop being the cliche dictator and CLEAN the OIL. When you fry fries at Burger King the Oil is changed 4 times. This seemes like it is changed every 4 months. Everything was soaking in grease. As if said owner never fried an eggroll in her life! You have to strain in- and twice before you pile it on. The fish: paper thin slices of frozen cod that will.make Gordon Ramsey slit his wrists. The dough fell apart as we bit and separated 3 slices of paper thin fish in hopes that it was fish...the Apalling! and to top it all off- the fries also frozen-were dark. Now look, I had heartburn all night and needed 5 tums to get through this situation. Incredible: the last thing is that the owner looks really busy, but I don't know what she was doing. Being a manager of a restaurant for many years- you can get sued for this kind of food and management style.
The KICKER: We see troll owner getting lunch from another restaurant, yes an Asian place, since the overpriced slop is not good enough for her. NEVER a good sign.
There's a time and a place for Fish and Chips, its not here- its not anytime soon at H Salt ( which btw nothing is salted here), maybe and more likely- in the owner's  back room sweat shop. But bring a hazard suit. Disgusting! and that young girl. Honey, Run. I feel like I paid 40 bucks to see abuse and have my heart attack 5 years earlier. Namaste North Hollywood.<//text>

< text>
About a year ago during my previous heavy use of social media,  I stumbled upon my highschool friend's (Ricky) post on IG regarding his and his brother Isaias' grand opening of their new own barbershop (1920 Barbershop)... although it's been many moons that Ricky and I have actually talked aside from the typical 'likes' and/or 'comments' on social media platforms, I was still very proud to see their accomplishments knowing that they've been in the barbering industry working for other barbershops for quite awhile. Due to my employment status with various jobs and also during my time in the military, I had been in and out of the 925 Concord area and state and also moved away from the 925, in which resulted in me having to find a barbershop closer to my location(s). As I was already living in Alameda and as soon as things settled with my regular job and transitioning out of military work, I decided to make an appointment with the shop to kill two birds with one stone -- simply say 'hello' and catch up with the brothers that I've friended since highschool (Ricky and Isais Huerta), and of course, stop by and support them by opting in for one of their gentlemen's cut services. MAN WAS I BLOWN AWAY! It really is the best feeling ever to receive a great 'fresh' cut, especially in a timely manner -- but... the VIBE of the shop including the Huerta brothers and the other fellow barbers and their clients.... definitely a great time! They've got great taste in music (chill vibes, in which now being in my 30s, I've transitioned to a much more 'chiller' state of mind haha), provide water/coffee, great hair products for almost every type o hair (and mind you, it's hard for a Filipino like me to find some good product to produce the hairstyle(s) I want due to the type of hair we have!),  awesome atmosphere with a definite '1920s' vibe mixed with a little modern stuff,  great conversations (aka 'therapy' hehe), and GREAT SERVICE OVERALL! Since then, I've been coming to the shop every time I needed a cut, despite now residing in Alameda. Why? Because not only are these guys my highschool friends,  the Huerta brothers AND their staff know how to work around my type of hair and understand the different 'cuts/styles' I mention to them despite the way I explain to them not being 'barbering technical terms' -- they follow through with a "I GOTCHU." statement, but also follow through in real time, producing the type of quality I like and love. I am also very proud of the way they handle the post quarantine lockdown situation, in which they've got signs all over the front door mentioning and showcasing the COVID-19 rules/workaround while being in the shop and receiving a cut/service -- MASKS ON upon entering and also a temperature check right then and there! Great job, 1920 Barbershop! üíà‚úÇüëèüèº< /text>

<name>Daniel David</name><date>1558678481194<//date><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
If you want a top grade cut, 1920 Barbershop is the place to get it! I've known the owners, Isais and Ricky, since 2013 when I first met them at the barbershop they previously cut at. Ever since 2013, I've been getting cut by Isais, and I can trust that my haircut will always be top quality when I go to him. He offers great advice on hairstyles and will work with you to make sure you get the cut you want and are more than satisfied when you walk out. I can guarantee that you'll look fresh once you walk out of there. My fade, line up, and comb over always looks fresh and I am always complimented by others with Isais's work. Both Isais and Ricky are personable and professional. They will make you feel welcomed every time you come in - it's like seeing family once you walk through those doors. The shop is clean and has that 1920s barbershop feel with a touch of modern to it. They also have a variety of hair products for sell, so if you need to restock your hair products at home, you can do so here! I don't trust anyone else with my cut besides these guys. I always make it a point to schedule my cuts in advance with Isais to make sure he is the one cutting me. I definitely recommend this barbershop to anyone in the area looking for a top quality cut!<//review>

< review>
The people are very nice, the music was great, the pastor was friendly,  but we were very caught off guard by the fact of that this church is very Pentecostal. There is people shouting out at random times, even during the service,  people speaking in tongues out loud without an interpreter as the Bible says to do,  people will laugh out loud, I have heard that  some people believe it‚Äôs the Holy Spirit coming over them, there is a lot of dancing and waving of the arms, and people gathering in front of the stage and doing all these things. Some people may be fine with this, but it is not what we were expecting at all, and it caught us off guard, And made us uncomfortable. Especially because they‚Äôre not called a Pentecostal church as far as we know, and they are very Pentecostal here at this church.  All these different things were going on at different times during the service, and for us it was very distracting.  We were even surprised to see that the pastor walked out and people were cheering and yelling for him as if he were a rockstar, and he started singing. It was very different. Not something you see every day in a church.  I just hope and pray that this church remembers what it is supposed to be all about and that they keep their eyes on Jesus.<//review>

<time>1620101162080<//time><Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
I'll admit, I always thought of Little Caesars as low quality due to the low price. I've had it a few times before and decided I'd finally buy some for myself. I tried almost all of the specialties, the extra pepperoni, the baked cheese crust, and the pretzel crust with cheese sauce. All three were great and the cheese crust with fresh mozzarella and basil actually tasted like the pizza you'd get from a restaurant. And you can't beat the price, paid less than $20 for all three pizzas. I was pleasantly surprised and I'll definitely be coming here for pizza from now on.<//Text>

< Review>
Slowly this location has bit the dust in terms of food quality and service. I have continued to go to this location for a year now and will now switch, just so I can have better consistency with my pizza.

I grew up in Michigan surrounded by Little Caesars pizza so I love the company and taste. This location however has continued to mess up called in orders, overcharged five dollars on pizza, and consistently produce terrible breadsticks.

I am not saying Little Caesars is the most gourmet pizza out there, but burnt breadsticks with no butter and very little cheese is definitely not what Mike Ilitch, the founder of LC, had imagined or produced when he started his own LC.

I hope more people stop going here because I know I am. I gave them multiple chances to get right and they just continue to disappoint.</Review>

<name>Renan Maurice<//name><time>1549941449258<//time><rating>5< /rating>< review>
I hadn't been to a dentist in a couple years, due to a bad experience. I finally had the courage to go see a dentist and my wife introduce me Dr. Alessandra, I can't begin to say how grateful I am.

From the moment you walk in you feel welcomed (thanks to the receptionist!). There's a nice cozy feel to the office.

Once you're in the dreaded "chair" Dr. Alessandra and her team of hygienists make sure you feel comfortable a ready. They are clear to communicate what they are doing and pause when the occasional break is necessary. For those looking for a distraction during longer sessions they even have headsets paired with Netflix!

Personally I had a lot to be done, cavities, crown and cleaning. All it took was two visits and were near painless and they reached out to me after each appointment to see how I was doing. In addition, Dr. Alessandra was also concerned with other aspects of my oral health and helped me create new routines and action plans to help prevent further damage in the future.

The hygienist I had was great. She took her time and wasn't rough with me.
Dr. Alessandra is seriously the best! To the way she went over my teeth with me and just chatting. She really helped me have an enjoyable experience!
After my first cleaning in 2 years I was surprisingly looking forward to the next time I would be in the office. Never thought I'd say that!

Just an amazing office overall!!!</review>

<review>Overall, I am a fan of Kaiser. I live in Seattle and I am a member. I also used to work at Kaiser. Just a top notch experience overall. Two weeks ago, my parents were hospitalized with serious COVID symptoms. One was hospitalized at KP Sand Canyon in Irvine, dad. My mother at Anaheim. They were hospitalized in two different places because of two different medical incidents. My dad rapidly declined and passed. My mom was on the second floor unit also in decline. The second floor doctors, charge nurse, attending nurses were outstanding. Since the situation was dire and under extreme circumstances, I was allowed exception to visit them both throughout their stay. My mom was then transferred to the fourth floor.  Never have I been treated from any medical professional or hospital with as much disregard and hostility than that  floor staff (charge nurse specifically) ... That includes working at two hospitals --- including Kaiser.  Right now, since the care of my mother is still in their hands, I will not file a complaint till after she passes.

I have been given conflicting information about visitation and then blamed for following that conflicting information. I have been kept waiting between 45 minutes to an hour for escort to that floor or just making deliveries.  We have left messages, legit medical questions and inquiries, five or six times, with no call backs.  One particular incident was particularly traumatic. My sister called the charge nurse and asked if I could visit. The charge nurse told her that I could because mom was in end of life care. I got to the hospital 20 minutes later, went to the security desk, a security guard asked me what I needed, and I said, "I'm visiting a patient in the fourth floor." He directed me to the elevators. I thanked him. I got to the fourth floor and was confronted by the charge nurse, asking what I was doing in the fourth floor. I told her she had talked with my sister 20 minutes earlier and approved my visit. The charge nurse then denied having that conversation and asked how I got past security. I said I didn't, someone from security told me to come up. She then asked me to wait outside the unit. security then came up and asked me why I had bypassed security. I said I didn't. The guard then said, "I didn't give you approval," I said, "no, someone else did."  I then called my sister. She then called the charge nurse and the charge nurse denied ever talking to my sister. The security guard meanwhile escorted me out of the hospital. I then said, "my mom is dying and this is how I am treated." The security guard than followed me and  demanded to know how he treated me "wrong."  At that point, I realized, that I needed to placate, since the care of my mom is still in their hands.

I called the social worker on the palliative care team, who had ensured that she was an advocate for us, and left a message of what had happened. That was two days ago, no call back.

My mom's last days will be in the hands of the fourth floor. At this point, I fear any responses from me, any complaints, etc. other than placation could jeopardize her care.< /review>< Pics>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
If I could give this place 5+ stars I would.

I've always been a big fan of Kaiser. I didn't get to be a Kaiser baby but all of my early care, teenage care and other needs have all been addressed by Kaiser because it's just easy. They have everything you need in house - a lab, pharmacy, and doctors for everything you need. You don't need to leave to get your stuff done anywhere else - it's all in house and that's why these facilities are so huge.

This is a newer location and so gorgeous - inside and out. There's a lot of parking, signs to point you where you're going, and friendly staff on the ground.

I was so impressed with how they handled things. Everything is computerized here. When a doctor comes to visit, they log it in a computer near your bed, then scan anything they give you - no charts, no paperwork - all technology. What's not to love?

Also the rooms are huge and spacious. They even have enough to give you your own room if needed but at an extra cost which is well worth it if you need that privacy.</Text>

< review>
My son - 8 years old - broke his arm on 3/19/15 and was seen by a doctor at Kaiser on 3/21/15 who decided against taking an xray of his arm.  The child was taken back 3/22/15 as the pain grew worse and at that point an xray was demanded and completed which verified the fracture.  The child was sent away again since there was not a radiologist nor a physician to see him.
We then started to make calls to the appointment help line to get our child seen and ended up having to drive to Mission Viejo - 30 minutes away and had to be seen there.  The child was seen and a temporary splint was put into place and we were told to call and schedule to have the cast put on by the pediatric orthopedics department on Monday.
Monday 3/23/15 we phone numerous times and are told it may be two to four weeks for our child to be seen for a cast as they only have one person that can do this.  As we were told by the staff the injury heals in 3-4 weeks on an 8 year old and at that point we are alarmed to hear that if the arm is healed improperly that the arm will have to be re-broken and reset.
We asked to escalate this as this is a ridiculous amount of time to wait and are told it will be escalated and the department will phone us no later than lunch time.  We wait until 1 pm and we receive no phone call and we start the process of contacting Kaiser again asking for help and are told that the case will be escalated and a case manager will be in touch with us in 8 - 10 business days ---two weeks.
This company has no business being in healthcare as they obviously do not care about someones health or well being an is willing to cause more pain to a child instead of finding a solution to their issues.< /review>

< Rate>
5</Rate>
<Text>Could not believe that they had such a great deal on MOLOTOW spray paint
2 spray cans for $5.00 dollars. This deal also includes some IRONLAK's which were beige's and brown's. Also which were also part of this deal were transparent white and transparent black. Sole writers at a local yard told me about this place and the 2 for $5 deal so i came right over to see what colors were left. It turns out that alot of what was left are matte finish colors which i do prefer. The gloss colors that were available happened to be CHALK PAINT, which us temporary paint that is easily removed with water, something that I am not interested in buying. Overall, they have a huge selection of Graffiti spray paint and the prices are pretty reasonable.  The pricing really gets competitive the more that you buy. Starting at 5% off when you buy only a few and all the way up to 20% off when you buy a 20 or more cans. I was also really impressed with the huge selection of acrylic paint markers like UNI, POSCA, SHARPIE, MOLOTOW, MONTANA, etc. I would recommend this place to my friends, especially when they have these types of Clearance Sales like the 2 for $5 deal.<//Text>< pictures>

<rate>5<//rate>< Review>
I live in Georgia and couldn't find a particular style ink anywhere in stock on my side of the country. After a relentless search I came across Art Supply Warehouse. I placed my order online and waited a few days to confirm my order, given this whole quarantine ordeal going. I had to wait a couple weeks from placing my order to receiving a package, but I want to personally compliment Mario, Gino and Owen for their attentiveness and eagerness to help! Owen confirmed my order, Mario confirmed what they had in stock and Gino shipped out my order. All three of them were wonderful to work with and I hope their supervisor sees this so they can get compensated cos these three gentlemen treated me with superb customer service and even worked with me on shipping since it took so long to fill my order. I received the items today 5/12 even though tracking said it'd be here on the weekend. My ink packs came in intact, sealed and in perfect condition. I will definitely be ordering from ASW again, even if it takes a minute to ship from one end of the country to the other. Again, a personal thanks to Mario, Owen and Gino! You guys are awesome!< /Review>

I love this place. It is always fresh and clean. The staff don't bother you but if you need help they are always nearby. They have a huge selection. I don't know how they fit it all in that little store. They now have a rewards club too. They always have flyers on events and classes. If you're into art culture this is definitely a place to check out. Honestly its the only place you should by your art supplies in Orange County. Everywhere else is overpriced and overrated.</Review>

< Review>
I discovered Art Supply Warehouse on a whim, by searching for an art store, hoping to find a real one. From the second I walked in, I found friendly faces and employees who (and I'm generalizing, I know) look like artists themselves (they are). After wandering around happily for I while, I sought help for my uneducated desire to give watercolors a try. I lucked out and got David, the manager, who went out of his way to assist me, from paint color choices to which brushes would be a good start.

I left happy (and supplied) and will go back again soon with my artistic kids. I highly recommend taking a trip here. You'll have plenty of brands to choose from and non-pushy help available if you need or want it. Please visit and help keep stores like these successful enough to stay open; there's just something wonderful about the scent of creativity you can't get online. (I mention this because the art store near me recently closed down, which is why I searched for another one‚Äîthere really aren't a lot left).</Review>

< text>
Great place for gathering art supplies at a really good price. After doing comparisons online directly on the sellers site as well as comparisons to other brick and mortar stores, art supply warehouse seems to have some of the cheapest prices.
The staff is all very friendly and down to earth and knowledgeable.
It's conveniently located near a freeway as well.

The parking is a bit tight though and the lot is shared with a small strip and has a large incline driveway, though there are side entrances too.

I can't recommend this place enough for anyone who does any kind of art, from street art to studio art, they have everything you need!</text>

< Text>
The one thing I can't stand is the fact that they have students and they're basically internships. I'm learning how to frame my own art and when I come in to buy materials, and want an opinion, help or I'm not sure what I want... because I'm new to this. they pull them away and say you are spending too much time with the customer? you need to come over here and stock? you need to go over there and do that? Well....I have a piece of advice for you all... especially the owner. the most important thing that you will ever teach these kids especially in an art supply is valuable customer service. if it takes 2 hours to help one person, you give two hours to help one person. you never know who they know, what they're going through and why they're there in the first place. Maybe they're sick, lost someone, maybe they help others and are time limited.. the last time I was in there... Was the very last. I was buying a book of archival paper, I needed help. I asked can you tell me... GAL interrupted " with a customer" as walking away. I said "absolutely no problem". She comes back, I'm holding a book in my hand looking at the specs on the front.. size thickness etc. she says to me rudely "I thought you said you needed help" huh? WHAT? Yeah I do... but don't hurt yourself..I SAID..I don't want your help now. go do what you were doing. just looking at something doesn't mean that I still don't need help! she literally turned and walked away, JAW DROPPED! So I just want to let you know AS I won't be back...I've spent $342.00 change in 3 trips within 2 weeks.  you have the most paranoid, lifeless, place of business. employees look afraid of helping a cust. Customers feel ignored, spend too much time looking for a few things on their own. Also.... I came in last summer with my daughter and I have a backpack, it's leopard non student looking... in the summer I use it as a purse.. we go to the beach, we go do things a lot and carrying a purse is not my favorite thing. I was asked to leave my backpack at the front counter? I said its not my backpack im a grown adult,it's my purse. they said well we need you to keep your backpack/purse up here at the cashier. WTH?  I have a question for you! why is it that I can't take my purse in your store, but you want me to trust you to leave my purse behind the counter with you? unattended by me the owner of the purse? I get it people steal but with your 596 cameras placed every 6 inches in the store, I don't think it's that bad... And I'm not coming back for 3 reasons.1 that you're teaching these kids its more important to stock things on the shelves that it is to help people. 2 anti trust issues having a person feel they can't walk in your store without first and foremost being looked at as a possible Thief. 3 lack of help buying the correct material. The archival paper book that I purchased I picked on my own it was correct after spending literally 45 minutes looking it up on my phone. the only problem I had with it was your rude employee and the fact that it was in a section that said it was $8.98 but I don't know when I got home I had spent $22 on it. More than half of what I wanted to spend or could afford to spend at that moment. Had that girl taking the time she would have been able to direct me to the correct paper still good quality but within my budget. I could go to Michaels Hobby Lobby and other places and find the stain items even online get better customer service in and out people who don't mind giving an opinion or the professional advice and spend less money. I looked at a matte cutter online and your prices were double for the same exact item your prices on this particular item were $9 more than Michaels you are not discount at all. I'm not an artist I like to create things and have fun and have a hobby. But I don't like being treated like I'm going to rip the place off simply because I have a cute leopard backpack. I go here about every other week, and it lives up to its name!  There are plenty of art supplies stocked in the aisles, from graphite pencils to gouache paint, and their supply of art books (used and new) covers practically every art topic you'd ever want to study.  They also sell a wide variety of paper in all different colors, sizes, and patterns; their selection of fabrics and sketchbooks is worth taking a look at too.  This is the total go-to place for any artist, even if you're a beginner or a professional.< /review>

<name>Deborah Weinstein<//name><Time>1519570271756<//Time><Rating>5< /Rating><Text>ASW carries a very wide range of materials and tools used by artists and architect-type people.  Prices seem fair to me, probably competitive with Dick Blick, but you‚Äôd want to do your own price comparison for large-ticket items.  There is a gallery space called Catalyst in the same strip mall as the store that is operated by ASW and used as both a classroom and exhibition space.  A reception there for a juried art show was the actual reason for our visit.  The show was nicely presented and well lit.  I think that organizing and hosting shows is a very nice (and smart) thing for ASW to do for their artist-customers.<//Text>< pics>

Then when I received the items I was short 7 of one color and 12 of an other.  It ends up in the shipping notification email in one small little part they mentioned that 18/25 and 13/25 were shipping, but that's it.
